  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Women for Health (W4H)</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">During the first phase of the programme (2012-2018) W4H had five outputs: (1) Increased training capacity of Health Training Institutions (HTIs) in programme states; (2) Improved management and financing of HTIs in programme states; (3) Improved quality of education provided by HTIs; (4) Increased HTI, government and community support for female health workers in rural areas; (5) Strengthened community based service delivery for women and children&apos;s health. During its extension phase (2018-2020) W4H has four outputs: (1) Increased, appropriate and better-quality training for nurses and midwives in conflict affected areas in Yobe and Borno; (2) Dissemination of the W4H approach to facilitate learning for sustainability and scale up; (3) Federal level agencies strengthened for better and more gender equal HRH practices; (4) State governments and HTIs in 4 states (Jigawa, Kano, Katsina, Zamfara) to strengthen capacity, policy and systems for sustainability.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The programme works with 22 health training institutions across six states, prospective health worker students from rural communities, existing midwives placed through the Midwives Rural Retention Scheme, Federal and State Ministries of Health, and the national regulatory bodies for health worker training and accreditation.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Women for Health is an eight year programme which aims to increase the number of female front-line health providers and support their deployment to rural health facilities where they can have greatest impact on maternal, infant and child mortality. The programme works in six states of northern Nigeria (Jigawa, Katsina, Yobe, Zamfara, Kano and Borno).</narrative>
  </description>
